Why Do Pharma Companies Market to Consumers?
The first question is an obvious one. It=E2=80=99s the one the Brits had. W=
hy do pharma companies market to the consumers when the consumers need to g=
o to the doctor, and the doctor=E2=80=99s going to decide anyway?
Pharma advertising has largely two main goals.=C2=A0
First is for undiagnosed patients. Increasing general awareness about a dis=
ease is going to make you more likely to see a doctor in the first place, w=
hich increases the chance of you getting the drug prescribed. For example i=
f you hear a commercial that says, =E2=80=9CIf you suffer from insomnia, ho=
t sweats, or are having nightmares that you have no idea where your social =
security card is,=E2=80=9D you might suddenly realize that you have those i=
ssues and there might be something to fix them. You=E2=80=99ll especially s=
ee that for disease areas which are lifestyle hampering or easily self-diag=
nosed (sexual issues, skin and hair issues, pain, mental health, sleep issu=
es, weight issues, stomach problems, and more). Below [https://email.mg2.su=
bstack.com/c/eJxFkEtuxCAQRE8zLC3AgGHBIptcw8LQ9pBgsPhk5NuHsSNFQrSaUnU1z5oKW8=
qnPlKp6H3N9TxAR3iVALVCRq1Anr3TRFA5cqaQ08wRySXyZV4zwG580DU3QEdbgrem-hQvB8aUo=
6dmjPMRi0U5RrkdlZss4dxxjomRfeida5rzEC1o-IF8pggo6GetR3mMHw_62c-X2U2E-kr5e7Bp=
f7-klqMJ5U_sZW0hmFy9DdA7OtG-g0JeU0wJ5mQklAksBjII5wSRC7fCrasDyxQsEsvJTSNgxtS=
D4X2jQ2lLqcZegSjrmOqSso9bl7-fZodwCf3jc697i76eM0SzBHA3k3qjvSjNG0TIHbmbTX0DxQ=
orNREh2c2gQxvFyJiYBOrJLnVX_A_9BUx7jsE] is some data on advertising spend by=
 disease area.
Fun fact, Claritin was really one of the first significant direct-to-consum=
er pharma campaigns with their =E2=80=9Cblue skies=E2=80=9D campaign in the=
 mid 1990s. Now allergy meds are all over-the-counter, so the spend has dro=
pped like crazy.
For already diagnosed patients, these ads are helpful for patients who are =
especially active in looking for different treatments for their diseases. T=
his happens a lot in diseases for which there=E2=80=99s high variance in ph=
ysician recommendations. Areas like cancer or rare diseases want to arm you=
 with information about a drug so you actually ask your doctor if the drug =
might make sense for your cancer type. As personalized advertising gets mor=
e targeted and the therapies themselves target smaller and smaller patient =
segments, ads for these drugs become a better investment. They have explode=
d accordingly.=C2=A0
What Are the Rules Around Marketing to Consumers?
As you can imagine, pharma marketing is murky and there are tons and tons o=
f rules around what you can and can=E2=80=99t do. But I thought I=E2=80=99d=
 just go into a few.
Rule 1: The product name has to be memorable for consumers but cannot be ev=
en close to confused with any drug that=E2=80=99s already on the market.
Quick game, which of these is a drug name and which are Lord of the Ring Ch=
aracters? Galadriel, Horizant, Zestril, Elendil, Denethor, Afinitor. Be hon=
est, you got less than 50% right.
Drug companies want you to remember the name (feat Fort Minor) but also wil=
l 100% get sued for trademark issues by other drug companies if you even sl=
ightly seem to be riding the coattails of their brand success. Plus, the FD=
A obviously doesn=E2=80=99t want consumers to get two drugs confused; takin=
g the wrong one can cause serious health issues. That=E2=80=99s why you hav=
e these very strange sounding, un-Googlable drug names, advertised directly=
 to consumers.
Rule 2: The advertisements need to say the name of the drug (brand and gene=
ric), at least one FDA-approved use for the drug, and the most significant =
risks of the drug.
While there are some nuanced differences between print, television, radio, =
etc. the general gist is that drug manufacturers need to give a =E2=80=9Cfa=
ir and balanced=E2=80=9D view of the drug. That means including the major s=
ide effects.
This is usually the most jarring part of pharma advertising. When an ad air=
s, it sounds like the drug is just as likely to kill you as it is to help y=
ou, and the side effect listing will happen over some lovely couple running=
 through a field of tulips or whatever so it doesn=E2=80=99t actually seem =
that bad. Non-US residents can see an example here [https://email.mg2.subst=
ack.com/c/eJxFkMtq5DAQRb_GWhq9LS20CAlZhGyGYWBmJfSotkVsqZHlNP77UXcvAkUV1OVy4=
ATXYC71NNeyN3Rftp1XMBlu-wqtQUXHDtWmaIikigmuUTQ8EiUUSru9VIDNpdW0egC6Hn5NwbVU=
8qOBMRVoMUKHSWimiL_gEDDzXkQtvfSKKUG0fHLdERPkAAa-oZ4lA1rN0tp1H9jLQN_73G638Sx=
HOzyMoWz3j2thGdj798De7Ef99fff59tJ54FK521YXM6w9ujP79eybVBDcuuOkqGYEiwII5RLLE=
cyyhglUV4EGS-XCIFr8AqrKU4MMOd64Hib6bgffm8ufN3pqJpcmi815bnHX4vbYH0E3YLtdztya=
qeF7PwK8SmoPT0_lNkZMtTuP1rX7naxxlpPRCr-FNINMsk4l5NEnRxLb-Uf6H_bA5RD].
Rule 3: There are different rules between =E2=80=9Cproduct claim=E2=80=9D a=
dvertisements, =E2=80=9Creminder=E2=80=9D advertisements, and =E2=80=9Chelp=
 seeking=E2=80=9D ads.
I was on the subway the other day and I saw what I thought was possibly the=
 worst advertisement I=E2=80=99ve ever seen. Oh you wanna know what this pr=
oduct is? F*** you.
This is an example of a =E2=80=9Creminder=E2=80=9D advertisement. It=E2=80=
=99s not actually making any claims about what the product does. It=E2=80=
=99s just reminding people who might already know about the product that it=
 does in fact exist. Really high-risk products will still have to include a=
 =E2=80=9Cboxed warning=E2=80=9D on these ads. These are different from the=
 =E2=80=9Cproduct claim=E2=80=9D advertisements I=E2=80=99ve been talking a=
bout where the drug actually says what it treats and how well it works.
So those are two types of pharma ads, but to make it even more confusing th=
ere=E2=80=99s a third called =E2=80=9Chelp seeking=E2=80=9D ads. These are =
ads that actually aren=E2=80=99t about a product at all, they=E2=80=99re ju=
st talking about symptoms of a condition generally and HAPPEN to have the l=
ogo of a drug company on it without talking about the drug itself, and will=
 say things vaguely like, =E2=80=9CThere is help, ask your doctor today.=E2=
=80=9D These kinds of ads actually fall under the FTC instead of the FDA.
